        html: '<p>The Dragon Warrior manual opens not with a button diagram but with the legend of Erdrick, the hero who defeated the Dragonlord generations before the game begins. The prose is deliberate and mythic in register — this is the story your character has grown up hearing, and the manual positions the player as a reader of history rather than a recipient of game instructions.</p><p>This framing device was unusual in 1989 and remains effective. By presenting the backstory as legend rather than setup, the manual suggested that Alefgard had a history independent of the player\'s actions. The world existed before you arrived. Your quest was continuation, not origin.</p><p>Enix\'s Japanese original had established this tone, and Nintendo\'s localization preserved it carefully. The manual\'s opening pages read like the first chapter of a fantasy novel whose middle sections happen to include enemy resistance tables.</p>'
